    <title>Quick Notes on Scrum Basics</title>
    <link href="http://example.com/2021/07/29/Quick-Notes-on-Scrum-Basics/"/>
    <id>http://example.com/2021/07/29/Quick-Notes-on-Scrum-Basics/</id>
    <published>2021-07-29T13:52:38.000Z</published>
    <updated>2021-07-29T13:58:34.164Z</updated>
    
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Quick notes of the Linkedin Learning Course “Scrum: The Basics” by Kelley O’Connell, with my own experience in the workspace.</p><h1 id="Problems-to-Solve"><a href="#Problems-to-Solve" class="headerlink" title="Problems to Solve"></a>Problems to Solve</h1><h2 id="What-does-the-Team’s-BACKLOG-contain"><a href="#What-does-the-Team’s-BACKLOG-contain" class="headerlink" title="What does the Team’s BACKLOG contain?"></a>What does the Team’s BACKLOG contain?</h2><p>A: a prioritized list of work that must be done</p><h2 id="Select-something-Scrum-Teams-do-at-the-end-of-every-sprint"><a href="#Select-something-Scrum-Teams-do-at-the-end-of-every-sprint" class="headerlink" title="Select something Scrum Teams do at the end of every sprint."></a>Select something Scrum Teams do at the end of every sprint.</h2><p>A: Demonstrate the completed work.</p><h2 id="In-the-Agile-Manifesto-Scrum-values"><a href="#In-the-Agile-Manifesto-Scrum-values" class="headerlink" title="In the Agile Manifesto, Scrum values _."></a>In the Agile Manifesto, Scrum values _.</h2><p>A: responding to change</p><h1 id="The-Heart-of-the-Framework"><a href="#The-Heart-of-the-Framework" class="headerlink" title="The Heart of the Framework"></a>The Heart of the Framework</h1><p>Agile Project:</p><ul><li>Product Owner</li><li>Scrum Master</li></ul><h2 id="What-are-the-3-normal-project-constraints"><a href="#What-are-the-3-normal-project-constraints" class="headerlink" title="What are the 3 normal project constraints?"></a>What are the 3 normal project constraints?</h2><p>time, cost, scope</p><h2 id="What-are-two-key-Scrum-roles"><a href="#What-are-two-key-Scrum-roles" class="headerlink" title="What are two key Scrum roles?"></a>What are two key Scrum roles?</h2><p>Product Owner and Scrum Master</p><h2 id="What-do-you-use-to-establish-ground-rules-with-the-Team"><a href="#What-do-you-use-to-establish-ground-rules-with-the-Team" class="headerlink" title="What do you use to establish ground rules with the Team?"></a>What do you use to establish ground rules with the Team?</h2><p>Team Norms</p><h1 id="Getting-Ready-to-Work"><a href="#Getting-Ready-to-Work" class="headerlink" title="Getting Ready to Work"></a>Getting Ready to Work</h1><p>Minimun Viable Product (MVP)</p><p>User Stories</p><p>As a <user role>, I want <user requirement> so that <desired benefit>.</p><p>Acceptance Criteria (AC)</p><p>Iteration (or Sprint) Planning Meetings (IPM)</p><h2 id="What-do-Scrum-Teams-use-to-break-their-work-into-small-deliverable-elements"><a href="#What-do-Scrum-Teams-use-to-break-their-work-into-small-deliverable-elements" class="headerlink" title="What do Scrum Teams use to break their work into small, deliverable elements?"></a>What do Scrum Teams use to break their work into small, deliverable elements?</h2><p>User Stories</p><h2 id="The-Roadmap-is-meant-to-apply-your-work-Themes-over-time"><a href="#The-Roadmap-is-meant-to-apply-your-work-Themes-over-time" class="headerlink" title="The Roadmap is meant to apply your work Themes over time."></a>The Roadmap is meant to apply your work Themes over time.</h2><p>TRUE</p><h2 id="What-types-of-estimation-do-Scrum-Teams-use-to-size-their-stories"><a href="#What-types-of-estimation-do-Scrum-Teams-use-to-size-their-stories" class="headerlink" title="What types of estimation do Scrum Teams use to size their stories?"></a>What types of estimation do Scrum Teams use to size their stories?</h2><p>Actual Estimation &amp; Relative Estimation</p><h1 id="Getting-Down-to-Work"><a href="#Getting-Down-to-Work" class="headerlink" title="Getting Down to Work"></a>Getting Down to Work</h1><h2 id="What-do-Scrum-Teams-use-to-visually-represent-their-project"><a href="#What-do-Scrum-Teams-use-to-visually-represent-their-project" class="headerlink" title="What do Scrum Teams use to visually represent their project?"></a>What do Scrum Teams use to visually represent their project?</h2><p>Information radiators</p><h2 id="The-Scrum-Team-must-always-work-their-stories-in-priority-order"><a href="#The-Scrum-Team-must-always-work-their-stories-in-priority-order" class="headerlink" title="The Scrum Team must always work their stories in priority order."></a>The Scrum Team must always work their stories in priority order.</h2><p>FALSE</p><h2 id="The-PO-can-add-a-new-story-to-a-Sprint-that-the-Team-is-currently-in"><a href="#The-PO-can-add-a-new-story-to-a-Sprint-that-the-Team-is-currently-in" class="headerlink" title="The PO can add a new story to a Sprint that the Team is currently in."></a>The PO can add a new story to a Sprint that the Team is currently in.</h2><p>FALSE</p><h2 id="All-of-the-following-are-TRUE-about-the-Daily-Scrum-except"><a href="#All-of-the-following-are-TRUE-about-the-Daily-Scrum-except" class="headerlink" title="All of the following are TRUE about the Daily Scrum except _."></a>All of the following are TRUE about the Daily Scrum except <strong>_</strong>.</h2><ul><li>everyone stands up ✓</li><li>it lasts 15 minnutes ✓</li><li>everyone answers the same 3 questions ✓</li><li>it lasts 30 minutes ✗</li></ul><h1 id="Wrapping-Up-a-Sprint"><a href="#Wrapping-Up-a-Sprint" class="headerlink" title="Wrapping Up a Sprint"></a>Wrapping Up a Sprint</h1><p>Retrospective</p><h2 id="The-Team-demonstrates-the-work-they-haven’t-tested-yet"><a href="#The-Team-demonstrates-the-work-they-haven’t-tested-yet" class="headerlink" title="The Team demonstrates the work they haven’t tested yet."></a>The Team demonstrates the work they haven’t tested yet.</h2><p>FALSE</p><h2 id="This-key-Scrum-role-is-the-only-one-that-can-accept-a-story-as-done"><a href="#This-key-Scrum-role-is-the-only-one-that-can-accept-a-story-as-done" class="headerlink" title="This key Scrum role is the only one that can accept a story as done."></a>This key Scrum role is the only one that can accept a story as done.</h2><p>Product Owner</p><h2 id="Why-do-Scrum-Teams-hold-Retrospectives-after-every-sprint"><a href="#Why-do-Scrum-Teams-hold-Retrospectives-after-every-sprint" class="headerlink" title="Why do Scrum Teams hold Retrospectives after every sprint?"></a>Why do Scrum Teams hold Retrospectives after every sprint?</h2><p>to recognize how they can improve their work practices</p>]]></content>
    
    
      
      
